==English==

===Etymology===
A loan translation of French ''[[danse du ventre]]''. First attested in English in the 1890s.

OED has as earliest attestation an explicit gloss of 1899,  "The ''danse du ventre'' (literally, "belly-dance") is of Turkish origin" (in ''Bohemian Paris of to-day''), but there are slightly earlier occurrences, in ''In the land of the lion and sun; or, Modern Persia'' (1891) of Persian dance; in
''Frank Leslie's popular monthly'' (vol. 36, 1893) "These women dance, not with their feet and arms but with their stomach. Hence their abdominal contortions are styled the 'belly dance.'"[http://books.google.com/books?id=CL3QAAAAMAAJ&q=%22belly-dance%22&dq=%22belly-dance%22&hl=en&ei=l4tGTdPIO4Wq8QPlluGuCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CFAQ6AEwBA]; 
and in  ''Untrodden fields of anthropology'' (1898)[http://books.google.com/books?id=-FgFAQAAIAAJ&q=%22belly-dance%22&dq=%22belly-dance%22&hl=en&ei=sopGTY73N4qV8QPK_sSmCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CE0Q6AEwAw] in reference to African (Wolof and Landoma (Baga)) dance.

